  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Anaphora is the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses, sentences, or lines. \u0026ldquo;We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds, we shall fight in the fields.\u0026rdquo; The repeated element creates rhythm, builds momentum, and signals that the items form a set.\nAnaphora is one of the oldest and most powerful rhetorical figures. It works through accumulation: each repetition adds weight, and the structure tells the reader that more is coming. Martin Luther King Jr.\u0026rsquo;s \u0026ldquo;I have a dream\u0026rdquo; speech uses anaphora to build from specific hopes to a vision of transformation. The repetition is not redundancy — each clause extends the meaning while the repeated phrase binds them together.\n",
